{
  "id": "evidence",
  "scens": [{
    "id": "map-scene",
    "menu": [],
    "text": [{
      "id": "map-scene-text 1",
      "header": "Sweden’s surface is 9% lake, which shows how important lakes are to the country’s environment.",
      "text": "The Arctic, known for its negative temperatures most of the year, hosts quite a few of Sweden’s lakes. Scientists have been studying them closely since 1913, allowing us to see what’s been happening to these precious ecosystems over the past hundred-plus years."
    }]
  },{
    "id": "context-scene",
    "menu": [],
    "text": [{
      "id": "context-scene-text 1",
      "header": "Here is what a typical high-latitude lake looks like.",
      "text": "- The vegetation, composed of birch and wild grass, is slowly moving north (this, again, is called “Arctic greening”) but collapses frequently, too (also known as “browning”)."
    },{
      "id": "context-scene-text 2",
      "header": "",
      "text": "- The area is quite rocky, as the lake sits on a bed of rocks."
    },{
      "id": "context-scene-text 2",
      "header": "",
      "text": "- Organic matter is transported into the lakes by runoff from higher lakes, precipitation, thawed permafrost, and wind."
    }]
  },{
    "id": "summer-scene",
    "menu": [],
    "text": [{
      "id": "summer-scene-text 1",
      "class": "caption-right",
      "header": "Summer to autumn",
      "text": "To see how the lake changes, switch between seasons and compare throughout the years. Click on the ice cover for flat charts to appear."
    },{
      "id": "summer-scene-text 2",
      "class": "caption-right",
      "header": "",
      "text": "Compare when the ice formed and how long it stayed each year. \nIce forms, creating oxygen bubbles. The longer it sticks around, the more algae will grow on it!"
    }]
  },{
    "id": "winter-scene",
    "menu": [],
    "text": [{
      "id": "winter-scene-text 1",
      "class": "caption-right",
      "header": "Winter to spring",
      "text": "All of this data is collected thanks to scientists’ fieldwork, as they sample the water at all points of the year and in any weather!"
    },{
      "id": "winter-scene-text 2",
      "class": "caption-right",
      "header": "",
      "text": "Compare when the ice broke, and how thick it got each year.\nIce breaks in crystals and almost never gets past a meter thick, but it’s enough to hold a truck!"
    }]
  }],
